It sets the node's pattern to K - use, then for each child in children (excluding parent), calls setParent with the current node's index as parent, and count as the number of used colors (starts at 1 or 2 depending on parent). Wait, in the Java code, the count starts as 1 if there's a parent (because the parent is already using a color, so when processing the children, the first child will have use = count (which starts at 1 if parent exists, then increments). Let me look again. In the Java code's setParent:

public void setParent(int K, int parent, int use, Node[] nodes) {
    this.pattern = K - use;
    this.parent = parent;
    int count = 1; if (parent != -1) {
        count++;
    }
    for (int n : children) {
        if (n == this.parent) {
            continue;
        }
        nodes[n].setParent(K, index, count, nodes);
        count++;
    }
} Wait, when parent is -1 (root node), count starts at 1.
